            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "So this really comes down to the type of buffer _requested_ by the applicable `write()` method.\r\n\r\nWith `io.BufferedWriter.write()`, it ends up parsing the _exporter_ argument (i.e. the Cython array object) as a `y*` argument code in the same sense as `PyArg_ParseTuple()` -- which causes the `flags` sent into `__getbuffer__()` to be PyBUF_SIMPLE.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, an `io.BytesIO.write()` ends up asking for a PyBUF_CONTIG_RO (which works fine), while `memoryview` ends up asking for a PyBUF_FULL_RO (which also works, as previously mentioned).\r\n\r\nThis all seems to be because the array's `__getbuffer__()` method is essentially _enforcing an unnecessary constraint **on the requester**_ (i.e. the `write()` method).",
